{%- comment -%}
  Reading time, in whole minutes. ONE source of truth — both the Journal cards and the article
  page render through this, so the number can never disagree between the two.

  Order of precedence:
    1. the `custom.reading_time` metafield on the article  (an editor said so — always wins)
    2. otherwise, derived from the article's own word count at 200 wpm

  The derivation is a FALLBACK, not the answer. It cannot know that a piece is dense, or that it
  carries a long recipe the reader will skim, so an editor is allowed to overrule it. But an empty
  metafield must never render an empty meta line either — hence the fallback rather than a blank.

  200 wpm is the usual English-prose average. The `plus: 199` before the integer divide is a
  ceiling: a 30-word post reads as "1 min", never "0 min". The `< 1` guard then catches the one
  case the ceiling cannot — an article with no body at all.

  Outputs a bare integer, nothing else. The caller supplies the label, so wording stays in the
  section's settings where a merchant can translate it.

  @param {object} article - a Shopify article
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  assign minutes = article.metafields.custom.reading_time.value | plus: 0

  if minutes <= 0
    assign word_count = article.content | strip_html | split: ' ' | size
    assign minutes = word_count | plus: 199 | divided_by: 200
  endif

  if minutes < 1
    assign minutes = 1
  endif

  echo minutes
-%}
